<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,766,1583]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,341,838,863]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Head as 
<figureCitation box="[512,589,838,863]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
and the proboscis from below as 
<figureCitation box="[957,1037,838,863]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
. Cheek with 5 bristles and jowl with 2 that are much longer and more robust. Postpedicels (
<figureCitation box="[755,835,874,899]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
) light brown and without SPS vesicles. Thorax brown with notopleuron and mesopleuron as 
<figureCitation box="[578,660,910,935]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles (
<figureCitation box="[249,335,946,971]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergites brown with many hairs which are moderately longer at rear of T6. Venter brownish gray with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[819,946,982,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Figs 96–98</figureCitation>
. Middle and hind legs light brown and front legs brownish yellow. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[530,610,1018,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 99</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 longer than 4. Mid tibia and basitarsus as 
<figureCitation box="[402,498,1054,1079]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 100</figureCitation>
. Hind femur as 
<figureCitation box="[678,773,1054,1079]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
. Hind tibia with about 20 differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[894,986,1090,1115]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–102" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[250,1337,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 92–102. Megaselia parhirticruss sp. n. male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 102</figureCitation>
) with exceptionally pale membranes, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index at least 0.3. Costal ratios 7.6: 4.0: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[1108,1206,1127,1151]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long. Hair at base of vein 3 small. With 5 axillary bristles, the outer being 
<quantity box="[730,827,1163,1187]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob grayish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,766,1583]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1198,1223]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[509,703,1198,1223]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
to Group V it runs to couplet 10 lead 2 or couplet 12 lead 2, but the very short costal index and pale wing membrane immediately rules out both species. In the key to the males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[348,502,1270,1295]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 95, lead 2 to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" authorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" box="[877,1125,1270,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hiticrus">
<emphasis box="[877,1001,1270,1295]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">M. hiticrus</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
. The latter has darker legs, with the crowded hairs at the base of the hind femur only gradually increasing in size towards the base (
<figureCitation box="[1331,1428,1306,1331]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–104" captionStartId="16.[151,264,704,727]" captionTargetBox="[183,1396,219,656]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,193,684]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 103–104. Megaselia hirticrus male. 103. left face of hypopygium. 104. hind femur." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617715/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 104</figureCitation>
) and the darker hypopygium has the left hypandrial lobe forked (
<figureCitation box="[881,981,1342,1367]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–104" captionStartId="16.[151,264,704,727]" captionTargetBox="[183,1396,219,656]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,193,684]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 103–104. Megaselia hirticrus male. 103. left face of hypopygium. 104. hind femur." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617715/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
). In 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz, H. &amp; Delage, A." box="[1033,1346,1342,1367]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" pagination="638 - 664" refId="ref7643" refString="Schmitz, H. &amp; Delage, A. (1974) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. 4 (33). Lieferung 301. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 638 - 664." type="book chapter" year="1974">Schmitz &amp; Delage’s (1974)</bibRefCitation>
key for Abteilung V it runs to couplets 27 and 36. With the first option it runs to couplets 69 and 97 where the hairs at the base of the hind femur immediately distinguish it. With the second option it runs to couplets 27 and 36. At couplet 27 the hypopygiuym and very pale wings distinguish it. As with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Bøggild" authorityYear="2019" box="[870,1008,1450,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomseni">
<emphasis box="[870,1008,1450,1475]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">M. thomseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below) at couplet 36 it runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" authorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paupera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">M. paupera</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
, which is only known in the female. The hind femur distinguishes it from 
<emphasis box="[1237,1385,1486,1511]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Bøggild" authorityYear="2019" box="[1237,1381,1486,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomseni">M. thomseni</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The costal ratios and more numerous posterodorsal hairs of the hind tibia distinguish it from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[1140,1270,1524,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paupera">
<emphasis box="[1140,1270,1524,1547]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">M. paupera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
